name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: God bless you all and God bless the great State of Nebraska!

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: Once again, thank you all for your service to the people of Nebraska.  Our work in the coming days will take a spirit of collaboration and cooperation for each of us to do our part to keep Nebraska strong.  I look forward to the days ahead.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: This year also marks an important milestone.  It is the 100th anniversary of women‚Äôs suffrage.  I want to recognize all the female legislators who have stepped up to serve our state.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: Senators Bolz, Chambers, Crawford, Howard, Kolowski, and especially Jim Scheer, who has provided tremendous leadership for the State of Nebraska as Speaker of the Legislature.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: Before I close, I want to recognize the State Senators who are completing their final session.  Each of these individuals has devoted the last seven years to serving their district and our state.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: But I also know that the citizen legislators gathered here today can get the job done when everyone rolls up their sleeves and works together.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: I know that there will be tough debates.  Long nights.  And an unpredictable journey ahead.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: Property tax relief.  Flood relief.  Veterans tax relief.  And growing our people and businesses.  These are four ways we can keep Nebraska strong and growing in 2020.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: As we implement this agreement, Director Frakes and I continue to look at next steps for the agency and what we need to do to keep our people and communities safe.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: And finally on the topic of workforce, I am recommending $8 million to attract and retain quality teammates in Corrections.  This will support the new agreement recently reached with the Corrections Officer union.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: My recommendations also include funding for LB 720, which would refine Nebraska‚Äôs business incentives.  It is critical that incentives are dealt with this legislative session, so Nebraska can remain competitive nationally as we work to recruit and expand job opportunities.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: I also want to acknowledge @u_nebraska President Ted Carter who has joined us here today ‚Äì we look forward to working with you as you lay out your vision for our University system!

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: I am proposing that we invest $16 million in scholarships for students at our community colleges, state colleges, and University system to help connect the next generation of Nebraskans with great careers in fields ranging from math and engineering to healthcare and IT.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: Connecting the next generation of Nebraskans to great opportunities in our state is key to helping our kids make Nebraska their home.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: Fourth, workforce and business expansion.  These twin issues need ongoing work in both the public and private sector.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: This week, you voted 46-0 for military retirement tax relief.  I want to thank you for advancing LB 153, and encourage you to deliver this tax relief that will help us retain our veterans.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: Third, we need to do more to retain our veterans.  Veterans continue to contribute to our communities and our economy after they complete their service.  Nebraska is the only state in our region whose veterans‚Äô population is declining in part because we tax retirement benefits.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: I am also recommending an additional $3 million to maintain an adequate balance in the Governor‚Äôs Emergency Fund, so the state is prepared to address any future events.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: My recommendation includes $50 million to address the state‚Äôs share of these projects and another $9.2 million to aid the counties most severely impacted by the disaster.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: Eighty-four counties and five tribal nations have submitted over $400 million in disaster relief projects to @fema.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: Second, flood relief.  Communities across Nebraska have been rebuilding, but there‚Äôs still a long way to go.  The federal government will step up to provide significant support, but the state must do our part as well.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: We need local spending restraint because, over the last 10 years, local governments have raised local property taxes 54 percent while inflation only grew at 17 percent.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: As we work together, I have three principles I am following: No tax increases, protect the Property Tax Credit Relief Fund, and encourage spending restraint in local governments just like we are doing at the state.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: I will be working closely with Senator Linehan and the Revenue Committee to direct this relief in a way that will make a difference in the local property tax bills Nebraskans pay.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: Today, I am recommending roughly $500 million in property tax relief over the next three years to help our farmers, ranchers, home owners, and businesses.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: Last year, we successfully increased the Property Tax Credit Relief Fund from the state to the people of Nebraska by over 20 percent.  This was a step in the right direction, but more must be done.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: First, property tax relief.  Property tax relief remains the top priority for the people of Nebraska and it‚Äôs my number one priority.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet:
In October, the state‚Äôs forecasting board raised its revenue projection by $266 million for the current and upcoming fiscal year combined.

With this fiscal framework in mind, I have four major priorities I am presenting to you today.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: A strong finish to the last fiscal year helped us rebuild our cash reserve and has created the opportunity for us to work on key priorities for the people of Nebraska.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: Not including property tax relief, the budget adjustments I am presenting to you today continue to control spending and limit budget growth to about 2.9 percent over the biennium.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: With the exception of a couple emergent priorities, I expect state agencies and our partners to manage within this two-year budget.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: Now, let‚Äôs turn to the legislative session, and what we can do to grow our state and #KeepNebraskaStrong.  Just a short eight months ago, we collaborated together on a two-year budget that set priorities for this year and next.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: Please help me thank the Nebraska Children and Families Foundation and all the incredible partners who have invested so deeply in Bring Up Nebraska, our kids, and our families!

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: Thanks in part to this work, the number of children in need of foster care in Nebraska has decreased by 18 percent over the last two years, helping to keep more children and families together.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: Nebraska is receiving this national award because of the incredible work that private and public agencies have been doing through the Bring Up Nebraska initiative.  This work is helping produce better outcomes for our children.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: She is in Seattle with Casey Family Programs accepting the foundation‚Äôs Jim Casey Building Communities of Hope Award on behalf of our great state.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: Nebraska is not just a leader in growing job opportunities, but also in our work in the area of child welfare.  You may have noticed that my lovely wife Susanne is not here today.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: Investments like these helped us win our third consecutive Governor‚Äôs Cup award for the most new investments per capita of any state in the nation.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: These strategies have been key in bringing great opportunities here to the Good Life.  Companies such as Costco, Google, Facebook, and Veramaris invested in our state.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: And I led trade missions to Mexico, Vietnam, Japan, and Germany to promote Nebraska‚Äôs quality products and to recruit new investment to our state.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: Together, we increased the Property Tax Credit Relief Fund by over 20 percent to $275 million annually, or almost double what it was before I took office.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: We continue to lead the nation in running government like a business.  In September, Harvard spotlighted the great work our Center of Operational Excellence is doing to put our customers first, cut wait times, and eliminate waste.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: We have connected numerous Nebraskans with great jobs and opportunities, launched new kinds of apprenticeships with @CLAAS_America and Graepel, expanded registered apprenticeships, and created new Developing Youth Talent Initiative programming.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: Our team at the State of Nebraska has been working hard to support new growth.  Over the past year, we‚Äôve used our four pillars of prosperity to grow Nebraska and deliver on our mission of making state government more effective, more efficient, and more customer-focused.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: And in October, we added over 15,000 new jobs, which is the fastest year-over-year job growth since 2015.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet:
In 2019, Nebraska outpaced the national rate for GDP growth.

In March, Nebraska marked the first month ever that one million unique individuals have been employed in our state.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet:
Even with these challenges, Nebraska has been able to achieve several significant milestones in the last twelve months. 

In spite of unprecedented flooding and other unforeseen challenges, I‚Äôm happy to report that the state of the state is strong, resilient, and growing!

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: As agriculture works to power through these tough times, each of us has a duty to be a voice for our farm and ranch families whether we come from a rural background or an urban one.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: And our continued battle to enforce a robust Renewable Fuel Standard has made for a difficult year for corn growers.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: An irrigation tunnel collapsed in eastern Wyoming, threatening our state‚Äôs sugar beet industry and hundreds of farm operations.  Trade uncertainty has shifted our focus towards diversifying markets for Nebraska‚Äôs ag producers.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: In addition to the flooding, we experienced several other major events.  A fire at a beef processing plant in Kansas depressed beef prices and hit our ranch families hard.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: Even though the floodwaters subsided and communities pulled together to rebuild, the events of the last year have compounded challenges for ag producers in our state‚Äôs largest industry.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: From the sands of war-torn Iraq to the highways and byways of Nebraska, Trooper Smith‚Äôs life was distinguished by service‚Äîa service rooted in his deep love for his family, his community, his state, and his country.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: I want to briefly honor State Patrol Trooper Jerry Smith who lost his life in a tragic crash last year.  He was the first trooper we‚Äôve lost in the line of duty in the last 20 years.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: And finally, I want to recognize the team at @NEMAtweets.  They helped coordinate the response across the state, supported local emergency managers, directed resources, and ran a joint information center among countless other duties.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: At the @NebraskaDOT, teammates sacrificed countless hours to keep people safe.  Since the flood, the agency has helped rebuild the state by reopening and repairing 3,300 miles of state highway along with 27 bridges.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: The @NEStatePatrol made more than 160 rescues in the weeks following the blizzards and floods in March.  Rescues were made using patrol units, light armored vehicles, boats, and a helicopter to reach people in danger and bring them to safety.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: During the flooding, members of the @NENationalGuard drove nearly 45,000 miles and put in 335 hours of flight time.  Along the way, they rescued 112 people, 66 of those rescues were by helicopter hoist.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: Even though God called James home earlier than any of us expected, he will forever be remembered for his selflessness and heroism.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: When local emergency responders asked for his help, James answered the call, put on his boots, and got in his tractor.  While driving his tractor to the rescue, the bridge he traveled over could not withstand the powerful water and collapsed.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: Sadly, the flooding claimed the lives of six Nebraskans.  One of those Nebraskans was James Wilke.  James was a farmer from near Columbus, who sacrificed his life while volunteering to save a stranded motorist.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: Nebraskans not only rescued stranded neighbors, but they also sandbagged levies, donated hay and supplies, delivered hot meals, and raised money for those who had lost everything.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: Through it all, Nebraskans showed the world what it truly means to be #NebraskaStrong.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: For 318 days‚Äîfrom February 4th to December 19th‚ÄîNebraska had a Flood Warning, Watch, or Advisory somewhere in our state.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: When we were faced with the most widespread and costliest natural disaster in state history, Nebraskans responded with heroic grit, determination, resilience, and generosity.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: As I have said before, I believe that 2019 will be remembered as Nebraska‚Äôs finest hour.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: From property tax relief to flood aid, we have several important priorities that we must address.

name: Gov. Pete Ricketts
tweet: Congratulations on the commencement of the Second Session of the 106th Nebraska Legislature.  I want to welcome each of you back to Lincoln, and I look forward to working together to #KeepNebraskaStrong during what is certain to be a fast-paced short session.
